segments.text: TRANSLATION Early Friday morning she woke up in a panic from loud barking nearby.
She sat up in bed, listened carefully, and her growls revealing teeth just beyond the door.
A shiver ran through her.
Dawn had not yet broken.
Only the first ray of light penetrated the gaps in the blinds, illuminating the clock hands at ten to five.
The barking continued along with the growling.
It seemed as if the dog beyond her door was engaged in a life or death struggle with someone.
Suddenly, she heard curses accompanied by footsteps running away, the loud barking accompanying the intruder's escape.
Only then did the noise dissipate, leaving behind complete silence.
It seemed both had gone on their way, the runner and the dog that had chased him off.
Slowly she calmed down, her breath returning.
What was a dog doing at her door?
It had been years since she had a dog.
It was one of the good things that had disappeared from her life all at once.
Another beam of light joined the first, casting some light on the Spartan room where she lived.
A bed, a chair, a small cabinet, and nothing else.
Now there was also a dog at her threshold.
She was afraid to open the door, fearing it might be a wild dog, one unaware of how much she loved its kind, one that didn't know she had her own dog from birth until almost sixteen.
But it was clear she wouldn't be able to return to sleep until she met this dog.
She got up, approached the door barefoot, pressed her ear against it, and listened intently.
Complete silence reigned beyond.
She opened the door just a crack and peered through it.
Nothing.
Absolutely nothing.
No dog and no burglar.
Maybe it was all imagined.
A dream perhaps?
But something didn't sit right with her.
She washed her face, brushed her teeth, got dressed, and then opened the door wide, looking right and left, sure the dog would appear at any moment.
Cautiously, she crossed the room area towards the kitchen door.
As she walked, she froze in place.
A large dog with ears perked sat upright on the mat at the kitchen entrance, waiting for her to approach.
Something in its posture assured her everything was fine.
She took two cautious steps toward him.
Only then did she notice his bright, beautiful, almost blue eyes.
She was captivated by his gaze, ready to swear he smiled at her.
It was a large dog, blue-eyed, part wolf with grayish fur, sitting calmly in front of her, smiling.
As if he had stepped out of a dream, forgetting he just barked loudly and shown his teeth a moment ago.
She approached him carefully, gently smiling back, extending a hesitant hand toward him.
In an instant he licked her hand, allowing her to stroke his mane.
She heard herself mumble to him.
Hey, handsome, where did you come from?
Who did you chase away?
You know how to growl and bear teeth when needed, but also how to smile?
He tilted his head as if listening, then rubbed his head against her leg, still sitting upright as if commanded not to move.
She opened the kitchen door and invited him in, but he showed no sign of persuasion, remaining seated at the kitchen entrance like a sentry.
She left the kitchen door open, hoping he might enter.
Meanwhile, she found a bowl, filled it with water, and placed it before him.
In seconds, he drank nearly all the water in the bowl.
You're thirsty, huh?
Who knows where you came from, and perhaps you don't plan to stay at all.
No worries, when you want, come in.
My door is always open to dogs who rescue me from unexpected intruders early in the morning.
Thank you very much, and thank you for being real.
You're most welcome to stay.
Feels like someone sent you to guard me, and by the way, they even matched your eyes to mine.
She spoke on excitedly, with an inexplicable joy, how happy she'd be to have him in her home.
Someone to wag his tail when she arrives, someone to talk to as much as she wants, someone to guard her doorstep and be entrusted with her security.
At night in the dark, when her eyes were closed and silence enveloped without any background noise, when nothing intruded and she was entirely with herself.
Somehow things gained perspective, became clear.
Suddenly it was obvious she had to travel to bait Yanai, to Naomi and David.
There was no way she wouldn't share with them the news she carries their grandchild.
Even if there would be moments of embarrassment, she deeply felt they'd rejoice with her and with him.
With this thought, she closed her eyes and slept.
In the morning, she dressed in her uniform, took a small bag, and stood at the junction to Hitchhike North.
The first to stop was Shmulik from the tractors.
Originally from Hedera, when he was still a playboy, he'd spent a lot of time at their pink house.
That's where he met his beautiful wife when she was a soldier.
Shmulik owned a luxurious Mercedes that didn't really match his simplicity and origins.
But when he saw her, he dropped the rich man pose, smiled ear to ear and said, What luck I have to pick up such a cute hitchhiker.
How are you, Shmulik?
Good to see you.
I need to get to bait Yanai, so please drop me off as close as you can.
No problem.
If you behave, I might even take you all the way.
I'm not rushing anywhere, going to visit my parents in Hedera.
No need to go overboard, I'll manage," she said with a smile, relaxing on the soft leather seat and unexpectedly listening to classical music playing quietly.
She found it hard to believe Schmulick listened to classical music.
It didn't quite fit this tractor driver with that music.
You've got great taste in music, Schmulick.
Delightful, she said.
You must be surprised.
Don't judge by appearances.
Though my dad's a farmer, my mom had musical education.
She taught piano and that music was all around our home every day.
Nothing relaxes me more.
Unfortunately, I didn't inherit her talent, and except for a bit of strumming the guitar, I'm not good at it.
Even strumming a bit is something not everyone can do.
I play my piano only by ear, and just like you, there's nothing more calming for me.
So, how's Joseph?
Haven't seen him for so long.
Remember how much time I used to spend at your place?
I'd come after work still dirty, and Lucy would welcome me any time, handing me a towel and sending me to wash my face and hands.
Yosef said I had special treatment because she only let me come in dirty.
But she insisted I remove my shoes outside.
So I'd sit at the bar barefoot, but with a clean face and hands, he laughed.
And then added quietly, maybe I shouldn't tell you, but I miss them, both, but especially her.
Silence fell between them.
Only Chopin's waltz continued playing in the background.
Schmulick glanced at her sideways.
The girl had grown.
The uniform with officer ranks added a certain seriousness to the maturity she already radiated.
He just hoped he hadn't upset her by mentioning Lucy.
What's taking you to bait Yanai?
He suddenly asked.
My boyfriend's parents.
She replied without hesitation.
And where's your boyfriend?
Busy with the army.
She replied smoothly.
Again, lies rolled off without fluster.
Not everyone needs to know everything.
But with Naomi and David, she'd share and worry together and not less silently understand together.
Suddenly there was an unexplained urgency to reveal to them what weighs on her heart, feelings giving her no peace, her love for him, and the child planted before he disappeared.
She sank into thoughts and Shmuit didn't disrupt, allowing her time.
When she looked up after a while, she was surprised to find they were at the entrance to bait Yanai.
Shmulik, you really shouldn't have.
It's my pleasure.
Now just guide me where to drop you.
Since we're here, I'll drop you by the house.
It's at the top of the hill, at the end of the houses on the cliff, facing the sea.
She felt urgency, her heart pounding.
It was her second visit there.
And the first had left such an impression.
And now they were on the entrance pathway, with Shmulik stopping for her.
Are you sure there's someone here?
Yes, of course.
Everything's fine.
Thank you, Schmalick.
It was a wonderful ride.
Seeing the Mercedes depart, she took a few steps toward the entrance and gently knocked on the door.
There was no response, so she knocked again a bit harder.
It surprised her that Brandy the dog didn't react.
A long moment later, she circled the house and climbed to the veranda overlooking the sea.
She thought David might be there, watching the waves.
Instead, she found an empty veranda.
Only the large, heavy wooden table David and Dan built together, and the cane chairs beside it, stood idly.
The house was vacant, not a sole present.
She made her way to the stable, and to her astonishment found it empty too.
Everyone had disappeared.
A heavy, uncomfortable feeling spread through her.
She cautiously descended to the shore, slightly folding the edges of her military pants, and stepped ankle-deep into the water.
A great disappointment filled her.
She'd finally mustered the courage to come to them, and they weren't there.
When she lifted her head, she saw someone walking slowly from afar.
And his dog beside him, suddenly the dog sprinted toward her and then she recognized Brandy the dog.
She leaped at her and they hugged and petted each other as she mumbled joyfully.
Brandy, sweetie, where have you been?
Who are you with?
Now he was close, an older man, his hair white, but his face suntanned and weather beaten like someone living by the sea.
He stopped in front of her and asked, how did you get here?
He didn't ask who she was.
Understanding from her encounter with the dog that she wasn't a stranger, she belonged.
I came down via the veranda.
I came to visit Naomi and David, but no one's home and the horses are gone.
And now I see Brandi is with you.
Internally, she wondered why she was telling him everything.
You're a bit late.
They left less than a month ago for a mission in the United States.
The horses moved to a nearby farm.
Noga's still in England and Dan's also on some mission.
I come here once a week to water the garden and make sure everything's all right.
He noticed the great disappointment on her face.
Sorry, it'll probably take time before they return.
Thank you, she said quietly, and the suntanned white-haired man continued on his way with Brandy.
Suddenly, without warning, her eyes filled with tears, her throat tightened, and a terrible sense of loneliness spread through her.
Look, Dan.
I'm here.
At your house, and no one is here.
And there's a small baby growing inside me, and I'm so alone.
Please come back.
I miss you so much.
I'm no longer that brave with my solitude.
I so long for togetherness.
Please, she spoke to him in her heart.
She then took a deep breath and made her way back up.
She straightened her pants.
put on her sandals, picked up her small bag and started walking along the path back to the village entrance junction.
She walked slowly, heavily, her head slightly bowed, slowly, step by step.
She covered the two kilometers back.
She passed houses, passed by people without almost noticing them until she reached the bus stop bench and sat on it heavily, healing extremely thirsty.
She sat there helplessly without any purpose, like someone who lost her way, sitting and staring ahead.
She had no idea how long she sat like that, until an old pickup truck with an equally old man stopped beside her.
Leaning on the window, his bald head glistening before her, he asked,
Hey, soldier, where do you need to go?
I'm heading south if it helps.
She quickly composed herself.
Yes, great, thank you.
She sat beside him, and they set off.
Again, she felt overwhelming thirst, realizing it wasn't just for water she thirsted.
She thirsted primarily for togetherness.
The bald man dropped her off at Ashdod Junction.
She had to hitch another ride, and when she reached home, it was already late.
He didn't talk much, the bald man, and she liked that.
In his radio played Israeli songs, which suited her just fine.

She wanted quiet, no talking, to immerse in her solitude, in the sad thoughts about Naomi and David's trip abroad, trying to understand why they hadn't told her before leaving, acknowledging she was hurt by it.
Opening the entrance door, she found a note with beautiful orderly handwriting at her.
Feet folded into four with two banknotes inside.
Thank you for the hospitality.
I assume I'll return next Monday.
I'd love to have the same room, and if you're not here, please leave me a key on the back window ledge in the corner to the left.
Thanks and see you, Yaakov.
That was Judge Yaakov.
It didn't sit well with her that she wasn't home in the morning and hadn't even offered him a drink before he left.
But she knew he was a very pleasant and quiet person for years he'd come for a day or two, once every two weeks, during his assignments to the magistrate court.
He refused to stay anywhere else.
She remembered he once arrived late at night and the hotel was completely full.
Her father transferred her to sleep in their bed and gave him her small room because he couldn't say no to him.
And now, once word reached him of her return, he resumed visiting the pink house whenever he had court duties.
She tucked the notes and slip into her purse, opened the windows facing the garden to air the house
and then stood by the kitchen sink, tilting her head and drinking gulp after gulp until she felt refreshed.
How thirsty she had been.
Hours yearning to drink.
Once calmed, she sank into her armchair, laid her head back, closed her eyes and tried to think of what to do next.
There are moments when bravery abandons her.
Loneliness overwhelms and conquers her completely.
She, who can do everything alone, understood that once Dan's child was planted in her, she needed togetherness.
Her hand moved on its own to her small belly, cupping, protecting, worrying, just wanting Dan to return already, knowing that as soon as he returns, everything will be fine.
